<subSubSection id="C31A6570781FFFFDBAB17E02BD1CD9D9" pageId="3" pageNumber="497" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BBF36FB781FFFFDBAB17E02BD1CD9D9" blockId="3.[151,1437,887,1525]" pageId="3" pageNumber="497">
<emphasis id="B974EAE9781FFFFDBAB17E02B81BD981" bold="true" box="[199,315,1391,1416]" pageId="3" pageNumber="497">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species resembles 
<taxonomicName id="4C004D78781FFFFDB8247E1CBBF5D981" authorityName="" authorityYear="1918" baseAuthorityName="Distant" box="[594,725,1392,1416]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Balclutha" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="497" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sternalis">
<emphasis id="B974EAE9781FFFFDB8247E1CBBF5D981" box="[594,725,1392,1416]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="497">B. sternalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C004D78781FFFFDB9797E1CBA82D981" authorityName="Vilbaste" authorityYear="1968" box="[783,930,1392,1416]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Balclutha" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="497" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="versicolor">
<emphasis id="B974EAE9781FFFFDB9797E1CBA82D981" box="[783,930,1392,1416]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="497">B. versicolor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in color and external characters, but can be distinguished from them and other species by the dorsal apodeme and socle of the aedeagus having paired processes, the very long subgenital plate, and the attenuate, spinelike pygofer apex.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C31A6570781FFFFDBAB17EB1BD4DD9FC" box="[199,1133,1500,1525]" pageId="3" pageNumber="497" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BBF36FB781FFFFDBAB17EB1BD4DD9FC" blockId="3.[151,1437,887,1525]" box="[199,1133,1500,1525]" pageId="3" pageNumber="497">
<emphasis id="B974EAE9781FFFFDBAB17EB1B86ED9FC" bold="true" box="[199,334,1500,1525]" pageId="3" pageNumber="497">Etymology.</emphasis>
The species name “longispina” refers to the long pygofer caudal spine.
</paragraph>
